external_knowledge:
- 'Top contributors' are determined by the number of commits they have made to the repository;
- Each repository can have up to 3 top contributors listed;
- The results are ordered by repository name and the number of commits in descending order.

- 'gardens with the most blooming flowers' refers to repositories with the highest number of open issues;
- 'flowers' represent open issues;
- 'watered' refers to the total number of commits, indicating the activity level in the repository;
- 'average age of the flowers' represents the average age of open issues, calculated as the difference in days between the current date and the creation date of each open issue.

- "garden of code" refers to the collection of repositories in the database;
- "blooming with the most popular programming language" refers to the repository that uses the most frequently used programming language;
- "gardeners tending to it" refers to contributors working on the repository.

- 'stars in their sky' refers to the number of watchers a repository has;
- 'captured the attention of at least one admirer' refers to repositories with a `watchers_count` greater than 0;
- 'most popular' refers to the top 10 repositories ranked by the number of watchers.

- "flourished with a vibrant garden" refers to repositories with high activity scores, which are calculated by summing the counts of commits, pull requests, and issues;
- "top 10" means the repositories with the highest activity scores;
- "commits, pull requests, and issues" are indicators of activity within a repository.

- "Popular" refers to repositories with more than 500 stargazers;
- "Highly forked" refers to repositories with more than 100 forks;
- "Details" include the full name, description, primary programming language, number of stargazers, number of forks, number of open issues, and number of watchers.

- "open repositories" refer to repositories that are not private;
- "blossomed with over a thousand admirers" means the repositories have more than 1000 stargazers;
- "caretakers" refer to the owners of the repositories.

sql:
SELECT name
FROM repositories
WHERE forks_count = (
  SELECT MAX(forks_count)
  FROM repositories
);

